Description: Orange / White Neutered Male Domestic Shorthair Cat

Age: 15 YEARS 6 MONTHS

Current Location: In RASKC Foster Home

Hi! My name is Oliver and I am available for adoption.

I was brought in by my previous owner on May 8th, 2018 because I did not get along with the other very young and rowdy cats in the home. My previous owner would describe me and friendly, sweet and lover of pets.

I'm a sweet, older gentleman who just wants to take naps, receive pets, get delicious treats and live my best life! I love pets and snuggling up in bed with my people. My caretakers have noticed that I do get along with cats that are closer to my age or cats that are respectful to my calm nature. I'm beyond past my young, rowdy, kitten days!

My personality color is BLUE. I am a gentle and loving cat who likes to take things slow. I may get nervous in new situations, so I am looking for a family who understands that I might need some time to warm up. Once I get to know you, I will be a very devoted friend!

A veterinarian has diagnosed or tentatively diagnosed the above-described pet with the following condition(s):

1) Renal disease. This pet has been documented to have renal insufficiency characterized by increased renal values and the inability to concentrate urine. This condition causes increase thirst and increased urine production. Renal disease is generally progressive and must be managed to maintain a good quality of life. Your veterinarian may recommend additional testing, medications, prescription diets, or supplemental care as needed.

2) Grade 2-3/6 heart murmur- A heart murmur was detected on physical examination. This means there is an abnormal heart sound when we listen to the heart. In some animals, this can indicate heart disease. However, other animals can have heart murmurs and never show any symptoms of heart disease. We recommend that you follow up with your regular veterinarian. Please see the handout for more information about this condition.

3) Moderate dental disease

As a result of these conditions, your pet may need specialized care consisting of any or all of the below. Please note this is not intended to be an exhaustive list.

- Special diet or prescription foods

- Prescription or over-the-counter medicines

- Special skin care or shampoos

- Regular veterinarian visits, which may include blood tests or other monitoring

- Possible surgery or other procedures as determined by your veterinarian

Adoption Fee: $30.00

Hi! My name is Armand and I am available for adoption.

I was brought in by an Animal Control Officer on June 11, 2018.

I am an affectionate lovebug who would be thrilled to cuddle up with you at home! I am an independent kitty who likes to do my own thing!

My personality color is RED. I am a spirited cat with a fun-loving personality! I may be sensitive to handling, so I would do best in a home with a cat savvy family who knows when to give me some space.

A veterinarian has diagnosed or tentatively diagnosed the above-described pet with the following condition(s):

1) Fractured pelvis. Fracture involes the acetabulum (hip joint). Surgical femoral head and neck osteotomy (FHO) was performed on 6/20/18. Cat is recovering well and will continue to need limited controlled exercise for another 1-2 months.

2) This cat tested positive for Feline Immunodeficiency Virus (FIV). FIV can cause immunosuppression and susceptibility to other diseases. Symptoms are varied but may include fever, anorexia, weight loss, or stomatitis. Not all infected cats will become ill, and those that do may be healthy for weeks to years before illness. Cats infected with FIV will remain infected for life and can spread the virus to other cats, usually through bite wounds. For this reason, FIV cats should be kept indoors only, and should only be housed with FIV positive cats or in situations where risk of transmission is unlikely. Please consult with your regular veterinarian for additional information and a management plan for your new pet.

1) This animal's skin condition is suspected to be caused by allergies. An allergy is an over-reaction of the immune system to an allergen. Allergies can be caused by environmental factors, fleas or foods. Allergies can lead to secondary problems such as skin and ear infection, or asthma. Controlling the allergen is the best treatment. Antihistamines, medicated shampoos, hypoallergenic diets and routine flea control are some treatment options. We recommend that you consult with your regular veterinarian about this condition. Received on: 2016-10-16

Description: Black Spayed Female Domestic Longhair Cat

Age: 11 YEARS 8 MONTHS

Current Location: In RASKC Foster Home

This is my friend Gertie. She is an 11-year-old adoptable cat currently living in a foster home. Unlike most fosters she's not in care because of her age or her health, but because of her attitude. When she first came to the shelter she was hissy and snarly and very difficult to manage. Ordinarily a cat that unfriendly to humans would be put up for adoption as a barn cat, but Gertie is front declawed and would never be able to defend herself outdoors. Her only hope was to get away from the stress of the shelter environment to see if some loving care could bring her back to the light side.

After months in foster care Gertie is a changed cat. Granted, she's still something of a curmudgeon and has definite opinions about how things ought to be, but she enjoys petting and brushing, and has a rumbling purr that she's happy to share. She is more than ready to go to her forever home, ideally where she can rule over her own private space. Gertie needs an adopter who is willing to learn her signals and respect her limits, and who appreciates that winning the heart of a "difficult" animal is well worth the patience it will require. Please contact Melodye Johnson - melodyej63@msn.com or (253)740-0269 (ok to text)

Hi! My name is Django and I am available for adoption.

I was brought in by my previous owner on March 20, 2018 because I needed a more low-traffic home. My previous owner was very sad to have to give me up and described me as outgoing, loving, playful and pretty much the best dog ever!

I love my people and want to be around them, cuddling and helping out with whatever tasks need to get done for the day! I have become a staff and volunteer favorite. Volunteers say I am very playful, I love my toys, and make a great walking buddy! On these nice, sunny summer days, who wouldn't want to take me home and take a walk or jog with me: I'm great on leash!

My caregivers have noticed that I seem to do well with other large dogs, but can be noisy when saying hello between a fence or gate. I would do best meeting any potential dog friends at the shelter before going home. (I have a big personality!) When meeting dogs in a new home, I would do best with a slow introduction.

My ideal home would be low traffic and with adults only. My previous owners let staff know that loud noises and lots of commotion makes me very uneasy and does not always bring out my best side. However, while in the shelter, I have done great with the positive and gentle approach that my caregivers have taken.

I am one of RASKC's Rover Scholars! This means that my adoption fee is waived and my adoption comes with a $400 training scholarship. Visit the Rover Scholarship Program page (under "Special Programs") to learn more!

My personality color is RED. I am a spirited dog with a fun-loving personality! I am still working on my manners, so I would do best with a family who is willing to work with me and help me become the best dog I can be!
